HOW TO EXECUTE YOUR FRONT SQUAT 🏋🏽

➡️ 3 Things you need to be doing to ensure you execute your front squat correctly, with confidence and to ensure your body is ready to make that successful lift!

✅ 1. Keep your back straight and chest UP
✅ 2. Keep your elbows high and facing forward
✅ 3. Use your breath to your advantage, creating internal pressure which acts like a belt to keep your core strong and safe

➡️ Set yourself before driving back up onto the top@of the box to full standing position 

➡️ Continue this to complete all of your reps.

💪🏽THE DEADLIFT 💪🏽

The movement that demands Power, it demands you to be on your game and it demands technique. 

Here are my 3 Top Tips to excuse the Deadlift

➡️ Foot Position - Close Stance - at least hip width & face both feet forwards 

➡️ Hand Position - Grip the bar just outside of your legs - not to narrow or wide. 

➡️ Load your posterior Chain - Tension in the hamstrings & Glutes while keeping your back parallel 

There are many other elements to consider when you starting getting into the lift in detail but get those 3 things right and your well on your way to executing a good solid deadlift where you can move some serious weight - Safely!

Note - if you come out of a deadlift where your back is really sore then take a look at your technique. The deadlift requires legs to drive the barbell up, not the back to lift it up on a hinge, this is where you will experience issues are potentially taking out the leg drive and putting all the work into your lower back.

4 GYM MISTAKES

4 Mistakes you maybe making that are stopping you progressing. 

They may seem obvious but these are the biggest mistakes people make all of the time:

1. Not following a Program. 

So many people walk into the gym and make up a session over and over again, or keep doing the same routine for months or years - get a program and follow it so you have a Plan and Structure. 

2. Not warming up properly. 

One of the most overlooked parts of training - prime and warm up your body and get it ready before you really start your session. This will improve your training and reduce the chance of injury. 

3. No progressions or overloads. 

To really make changes you need to improve and inside the gym you want to get stronger and fitter. You program should consist of building up weights and intensity overtime - start progressively overloading your body to make it adapt, grow and get stronger. 

4. Not tracking your progress. 

If I ask you X (What’s your max Squat, Press, Deadlift etc) you should know - Maxes will always give you a bench mark to base your training on with % work and times for workouts or distances.  It’s like not knowing your date of birth! Start tracking your fitness!

How to execute this movement ⬇️

First the Turkish get is always challenging and one that demands stability and strength, it will show any weaknesses - which is always a good thing. 

If you are new to the movement select a lighter weight, so you can first get the movement pattern correct and execute it with quality form, then start building the weight. 

➡️ Lay down - kettlebell upright in one hand - same knee up as the hand you have the kettlebell in

➡️ Whilst pushing the kettlebell up to the ceiling, roll up and over before placing your opposite hand down onto the floor to act as support.

➡️ Put your weight into the hand allowing leg to kick back through and position your knee into the floor 

➡️ From here, keep pushing the Kettlebell up with a fully locked out arm, go into kneeling position before standing up fully. 

➡️ Once stood up, control your decent back down the same way to finish the movement. 

🔥 Ensure your arm is always locked out and the kettlebell is being held overhead - keep your core braces the light for maximum control and quality.

 1. Start with proper setup: Stand with your feet hip-width apart, toes pointing forward, and grip the barbell with an overhand grip at shoulder width.

 2. Hinge at the hips: Initiate the movement by pushing your hips back, maintaining a slight bend in your knees. Keep your chest up and shoulders back throughout the lift.

 3. Maintain a neutral spine: As you lower the barbell, focus on keeping your spine in a neutral position.

 4. Control the descent: Lower the barbell by pushing your hips back and maintaining tension in your hamstrings. Keep the barbell close to your body as you lower. 

 5. Engage your glutes and hamstrings: As you lift the barbell back up, drive through your heels, squeeze your glutes, and engage your hamstrings.

3 Core Movements you need ⬇️

➡️ Hanging Knee Tuck Holds: This exercise involves hanging from a bar and tucking your knees up towards your chest while maintaining control and stability. It primarily targets the lower abdominal muscles, hip flexors, and lower back. Hanging knee tuck holds are beneficial for core strength as they engage multiple muscle groups simultaneously, helping to improve overall core stability, balance, and control. They also enhance grip strength and shoulder stability due to the hanging position.

➡️ Russian Kettlebell Twists: Russian kettlebell twists are performed by sitting on the ground, holding a kettlebell or any weighted object, and rotating the torso from side to side. This movement targets the obliques, which are the muscles on the sides of the abdomen. It helps to strengthen the rotational muscles of the core, improving spinal mobility and stability. Russian kettlebell twists also engage the hip muscles and shoulders, promoting full-body coordination and functional strength.

➡️ Copenhagen Plank Holds: The Copenhagen plank hold is a challenging exercise that involves placing one foot on an elevated platform while assuming a plank position. This movement primarily targets the obliques, hip muscles, and stabilizing muscles of the core. By creating an unstable environment for the core muscles, Copenhagen plank holds help to improve core strength, balance, and stability. They also enhance hip strength and mobility, which is beneficial for various athletic activities and daily movements.

Incorporating these 3 core movements into your training program can provide a well-rounded approach to core strength. They target different muscle groups within the core, promoting overall stability, balance, and functional strength. Remember to perform these exercises with proper form and gradually increase the intensity as your core strength improves.

Barbell Walking Lunge

How to execute:

 1. Start by standing upright with a barbell across your upper back.
 2. Take a step forward with one leg, lowering your body until your front knee is bent at a  90-degree angle.
 3. Push through your front heel to stand back up and bring your back leg forward to take a step.
 4. Repeat the movement, alternating legs with each step.

 Main benefits:

 1. Strength: The barbell walking lunge engages your leg muscles, including quadriceps, hamstrings, and glutes, helping to build lower body strength.

 2. Core Stability: Maintaining balance during the movement requires core activation, which helps improve stability and overall core strength.

 3. Muscle Growth: The barbell walking lunge targets multiple muscle groups simultaneously, promoting muscle growth and development in the legs, hips, and glutes.

 4. Functional Movement: This exercise mimics the walking motion, making it a functional movement that can improve everyday activities and sports performance.

 5. Balance and Coordination: The unilateral nature of the exercise challenges your balance and coordination, enhancing overall body control and stability.

These benefits make the barbell walking lunge a great exercise for improving strength, core stability, muscle growth, functional movement, and balance.

As far as stretching goes this one is golden and here is why:

Stretching the lats and abdominals can provide several benefits for the body and prep for training ⬇️

 1. Improved flexibility: Stretching the lats and abdominals helps increase the range of motion in these muscles, allowing for better flexibility and mobility in the upper body.

 2. Reduced muscle tension: Regular stretching of the lats and abdominals can help alleviate muscle tension and tightness in these areas, promoting relaxation and reducing the risk of muscle imbalances.

 3. Enhanced posture and core stability: Stretching the lats and abdominals can contribute to better posture and core stability. By lengthening and strengthening these muscles, you can support a more upright posture and improve overall body alignment.

Why ? The Bulgarian Split Squat explained ⬇️

5 benefits of the Bulgarian split squat: 

 1. Targeted Leg Muscles: The Bulgarian split squat primarily targets the quadriceps, hamstrings, and glutes. This exercise helps to strengthen and tone these muscles, leading to improved leg definition and overall lower body strength.

 2. Balance and Stability: Performing the Bulgarian split squat requires maintaining balance and stability, as one leg is elevated behind you. This helps to improve proprioception and coordination, leading to better overall balance and stability in your lower body.

 3. Single-Leg Strength: Since the Bulgarian split squat is a unilateral exercise, it helps to address any strength imbalances between your legs. By focusing on one leg at a time, you can develop equal strength in both legs, reducing the risk of injuries and improving overall athletic performance.

 4. Increased Range of Motion: The Bulgarian split squat requires a deeper range of motion compared to traditional squats. This increased range of motion helps to improve hip mobility and flexibility, leading to better overall movement patterns and reduced risk of injury.

 5. Core Engagement: Balancing on one leg during the Bulgarian split squat activates your core muscles to maintain stability. This exercise can help to strengthen your core and improve your overall functional strength.
